      <!-- What Is Tramp Oil -->
      <div class="bg-white rounded-xl border border-gray-200 p-6 shadow-sm mb-6">
        <h2 class="text-xl font-bold text-navy mb-4">What Is Tramp Oil?</h2>
        <div class="space-y-3 text-text-light">
          <img src="/images/tramp-oil-centrifuge/Alfa-Laval-WSPX-307-Water-Based-Coolant-Centrifuge.jpg" alt="Alfa Laval WSPX-307 Water-Based Coolant Centrifuge for tramp oil separation" width="750" height="505" loading="lazy" class="rounded-lg w-full mb-4" />
          <p>Tramp oil is petroleum-based lubricant that enters a metalworking coolant sump from sources other than the coolant itself. Unlike the water-soluble coolant concentrate intentionally mixed into the sump, tramp oil is an uninvited contaminant originating from:</p>
          <ul class="list-disc list-inside space-y-2 ml-2">
            <li><strong class="text-navy">Machine tool lubrication systems:</strong> Hydraulic oil, slideway oil, and spindle lubricants leak from machine tool components directly into the coolant sump over time. Even a well-maintained machine tool may contribute 1–5 liters of tramp oil per week.</li>
            <li><strong class="text-navy">Parts transport oils:</strong> Residual machining oils from incoming workpieces drip into the coolant as parts are machined.</li>
            <li><strong class="text-navy">Rust preventive oils:</strong> Anti-corrosion coatings applied to incoming material or fixtures dissolve partially into the coolant.</li>
            <li><strong class="text-navy">Forklift and overhead crane drips:</strong> In facilities with busy material handling operations, petroleum drips reach coolant sumps.</li>
          </ul>
          <p>In a typical machining facility, an active coolant sump accumulates tramp oil at 0.5–3% of sump volume per week. A 2,000-liter sump may be gaining 10–60 liters of tramp oil per week — enough to cause serious contamination problems within days to weeks if not removed.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- Why It Must Be Removed -->
      <div class="bg-white rounded-xl border border-gray-200 p-6 shadow-sm mb-6">
        <h2 class="text-xl font-bold text-navy mb-4">Why Tramp Oil Must Be Removed</h2>
        <div class="space-y-3 text-text-light">
          <p>Tramp oil is more than an aesthetic problem. Its presence in the coolant system causes a cascade of degradation effects:</p>

          <h3 class="font-semibold text-navy">Bacterial Growth and Coolant Degradation</h3>
          <p>Tramp oil coats the surface of the coolant sump with an oxygen-limiting film. Beneath this film, anaerobic bacteria thrive — breaking down the coolant's biocide package, consuming emulsifiers, and producing sulfurous compounds that cause the characteristic rotten-egg smell of a failed coolant. A sump with high tramp oil content may require complete dump-and-recharge every 2–4 weeks rather than every 6–12 months, representing enormous coolant cost and disposal expense.</p>

          <h3 class="font-semibold text-navy">Tool Wear and Surface Finish Degradation</h3>
          <p>Effective coolant must reach the cutting zone as a uniform emulsion. Tramp oil disrupts the emulsion stability, causing inconsistent tool lubrication and cooling. The result is accelerated tool wear, shorter tool life, and degraded surface finish quality — all directly impacting production cost and reject rates.</p>

          <h3 class="font-semibold text-navy">Foam Generation</h3>
          <p>Tramp oil — particularly hydraulic oil — reacts with coolant emulsifiers to generate persistent foam. Foam reduces coolant flow, causes pump cavitation, makes sump level monitoring unreliable, and creates housekeeping problems as foam overflows sumps.</p>

          <h3 class="font-semibold text-navy">Worker Health Hazards</h3>
          <p>Tramp oil in coolant aerosol (mist) is a recognized occupational health hazard. The fine oil droplets generated during high-speed machining operations carry bacteria and irritating compounds that cause dermatitis and respiratory irritation. NIOSH and OSHA have established coolant mist exposure limits specifically because of this risk. Removing tramp oil significantly reduces mist toxicity.</p>

          <h3 class="font-semibold text-navy">Machine Staining and Corrosion</h3>
          <p>Tramp-oil-contaminated coolant loses its rust inhibitor effectiveness — leading to surface staining on machined parts and corrosion on machine tool surfaces. Rework and part rejection costs from corrosion-related issues can be significant.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- How a Disc Centrifuge Removes It -->
      <div class="bg-white rounded-xl border border-gray-200 p-6 shadow-sm mb-6">
        <h2 class="text-xl font-bold text-navy mb-4">How a Disc Centrifuge Removes Tramp Oil</h2>
        <div class="space-y-3 text-text-light">
          <img src="/images/tramp-oil-centrifuge/Alfa-Laval-WSPX303-Coolant-Centrifuge.jpg" alt="Machine coolant centrifuge for tramp oil removal - WSPX303 model" width="400" height="400" loading="lazy" class="rounded-lg mx-auto mb-4" />
          <p>Tramp oil separation is an ideal application for disc centrifuge technology because the separation challenge is purely a density difference between two liquids — exactly what disc centrifuges are engineered to exploit.</p>
          <p>Petroleum-based tramp oils have specific gravities of approximately 0.85–0.90 g/cm³. Metalworking coolant (water-based emulsion at typical concentrations) has a specific gravity of approximately 0.99–1.00 g/cm³. This density difference of 0.09–0.15 g/cm³ is sufficient for disc centrifuge separation at 6,000–9,000× gravity.</p>
          <p>The separation process:</p>
          <ol class="list-decimal list-inside space-y-2 ml-2">
            <li>Contaminated coolant is pumped from the sump to the centrifuge feed inlet at a controlled flow rate.</li>
            <li>Inside the rotating disc stack, the density difference between tramp oil and coolant is amplified by centrifugal force. Coolant (denser) moves outward; tramp oil (lighter) concentrates in the inner zone.</li>
            <li>Clarified coolant exits through the light phase outlet — in this application, the coolant is the "heavy" phase being clarified of even lighter tramp oil.</li>
            <li>Concentrated tramp oil accumulates and is continuously discharged through the heavy-phase (actually light-density) outlet or via periodic bowl discharge.</li>
            <li>Fine metal swarf particles present in the coolant are simultaneously removed as solids, accumulating in the bowl sludge space and discharged periodically.</li>
          </ol>
          <p>The result is coolant returning to the sump with tramp oil content reduced to below 0.1% — essentially free of tramp oil contamination on a continuous basis.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- Comparison to Alternatives -->
      <div class="bg-white rounded-xl border border-gray-200 p-6 shadow-sm mb-6">
        <h2 class="text-xl font-bold text-navy mb-4">Comparison to Skimmers and Coalescers</h2>
        <div class="space-y-3 text-text-light">
          <img src="/images/tramp-oil-centrifuge/Alfa-Laval-WSPX-307-Coolant-Centrifuge-600.jpg" alt="Alfa Laval WSPX-307 coolant centrifuge compared to conventional tramp oil removal methods" width="600" height="423" loading="lazy" class="rounded-lg w-full mb-4" />
          <p>Tramp oil skimmers and gravity coalescers are simpler and less expensive than centrifuges, but they have significant limitations:</p>
          <ul class="list-disc list-inside space-y-2 ml-2">
            <li><strong class="text-navy">Belt/disk skimmers:</strong> Remove only the free-floating surface layer of tramp oil. Emulsified or finely dispersed tramp oil — which accounts for most of the contamination in an active sump — passes through completely untouched. Effectiveness: typically 20–40% tramp oil reduction.</li>
            <li><strong class="text-navy">Gravity coalescers:</strong> Use media to coalesce small oil droplets into larger ones that float to the surface for skimming. More effective than skimmers alone, but still limited to droplets larger than approximately 50–100 microns. Fine emulsified oil passes through. Effectiveness: typically 40–70% tramp oil reduction. Also requires media replacement and cleaning.</li>
            <li><strong class="text-navy">Disc centrifuge:</strong> Operates at 6,000–10,000× gravity, separating oil droplets down to 1–2 micron size. Removes both free and emulsified tramp oil simultaneously. Also removes fine metal fines as a bonus. Effectiveness: typically 90–99%+ tramp oil reduction.</li>
          </ul>
          <p>For sumps where tramp oil control is critical to coolant life and part quality, the centrifuge delivers results that skimmers and coalescers simply cannot match.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- Flow Rates and Sizing -->
      <div class="bg-white rounded-xl border border-gray-200 p-6 shadow-sm mb-6">
        <h2 class="text-xl font-bold text-navy mb-4">Flow Rates and Centrifuge Sizing</h2>
        <div class="space-y-3 text-text-light">
          <p>Sizing a tramp oil centrifuge for a coolant sump application requires two inputs: the sump volume and the tramp oil ingress rate.</p>
          <p>As a general rule, the centrifuge should be capable of processing the entire sump volume in 4–8 hours during continuous operation. This "turnover time" ensures that tramp oil entering the sump is captured before it builds to damaging concentrations.</p>
          <ul class="list-disc list-inside space-y-2 ml-2">
            <li><strong class="text-navy">Small sump (500–2,000 L):</strong> 200–500 L/hour centrifuge capacity typically sufficient</li>
            <li><strong class="text-navy">Medium sump (2,000–10,000 L):</strong> 1,000–2,500 L/hour</li>
            <li><strong class="text-navy">Large central sump or multiple machines (10,000–50,000 L):</strong> 3,000–10,000+ L/hour; may use multiple centrifuges or a larger industrial model</li>
          </ul>
