        <h2 class="text-xl font-bold text-navy mb-4">ROI of Tramp Oil Removal</h2>
        <div class="space-y-3 text-text-light">
          <p>The return on investment for a tramp oil centrifuge is typically faster than most capital equipment purchases. The savings come from multiple sources simultaneously:</p>
          <ul class="list-disc list-inside space-y-2 ml-2">
            <li><strong class="text-navy">Coolant extension:</strong> Sumps contaminated with tramp oil require dump-and-recharge every 2–8 weeks. Clean sumps typically run 6–18 months. For a 5,000-liter sump with coolant cost of $20/liter, avoiding even two extra dump cycles per year saves $200,000 annually.</li>
            <li><strong class="text-navy">Reduced coolant concentrate usage:</strong> Bacteria-degraded coolant loses concentration faster, requiring more frequent concentrate additions to maintain the correct mixing ratio. Removing tramp oil stabilizes coolant concentration and reduces concentrate consumption 20–40%.</li>
            <li><strong class="text-navy">Waste disposal cost reduction:</strong> Spent coolant is regulated waste with disposal costs of $0.20–$0.80 per liter. Halving the frequency of sump dumps halves the disposal cost.</li>
            <li><strong class="text-navy">Tool life improvement:</strong> Facilities consistently report 15–30% improvement in tool life after implementing effective tramp oil removal, from restored coolant lubrication and cooling performance.</li>
            <li><strong class="text-navy">Reduced maintenance and downtime:</strong> Cleaner sumps mean fewer pump clogs, cleaner filters, and less machine maintenance related to coolant degradation.</li>
          </ul>
          <p>Contact Dolphin Centrifuge to discuss a specific ROI analysis for your facility — the numbers are often compelling enough to justify expedited purchase approval.</p>
        </div>
